'''Tahoka''' is a city in and the [[county seat]] of [[Lynn County, Texas|Lynn County]], [[Texas]], [[United States]].{{GR|6}} The population was 2,910 at the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]].

==Geography==
Tahoka is located at {{coord|33|9|57|N|101|47|58|W|type:city}} (33.165804, -101.799315){{GR|1}}.

According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|2.4|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|2.4|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and 0.42% is water.

==Demographics==
As of the [[census]]{{GR|2}} of 2000, there were 2,910 people, 1,063 households, and 783 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,213.9 people per square mile (468.1/km<U+00B2>). There were 1,194 housing units at an average density of 498.1 per square mile (192.1/km<U+00B2>). The racial makeup of the city was 74.71% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 5.46% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 1.37% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.10% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 16.36% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.99% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 44.78% of the population.

There were 1,063 households out of which 39.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 54.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 26.3% were non-families. 25.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.70 and the average family size was 3.22.

In the city the population was spread out with 32.0% under the age of 18, 7.3% from 18 to 24, 26.0% from 25 to 44, 19.5% from 45 to 64, and 15.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females there were 92.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 85.6 males.

The median income for a household in the city was $23,214, and the median income for a family was $30,200. Males had a median income of $29,293 versus $20,346 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $13,145. About 21.6% of families and 24.2% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 25.7% of those under age 18 and 32.9% of those age 65 or over.

Tahoka is served by a weekly newspaper, nearby stations [[KBXJ|KBXJ (FM)]] and [[KPET (AM)]], and the various Lubbock radio and TV stations. [[KAMZ|KAMZ (FM)]] and [[KMMX|KMMX (FM)]] are licensed to Tahoka, but have offices and studios in Lubbock and originate few if any programs fron Lynn county.

==Education==
The city of Tahoka is served by the [[Tahoka Independent School District]].

==Notable residents==
*'''Mildred W. Abbe''' (1914<U+2013>2008) was named "Woman of the Year" in 1987 by the Tahoka [[Chamber of Commerce]]. A former Texas Senior [[Poet Laureate]], she was active with the Pioneer Museum of Lynn County and the [[Baptist]] church. A native of [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], Mrs. Abbe and her husband, Robert E. Abbe, Sr. (1915<U+2013>1977) came to [[Lubbock, Texas|Lubbock]] and then Tahoka through his employment with the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]. She was survived by a son, '''Donald R. Abbe''', a former [[history]] [[professor]] at [[Texas Tech University]] in Lubbock who wrote a history of Lynn County, and two daughters, Barbara Abbe and Reda Abbe. A second son was Robert E. "Buster" Abbe, Jr. (1943<U+2013>2002).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lubbockonline.com/stories/030708/obi_254607473.shtml|title=Mildred W. Abbe|publisher=''[[Lubbock Avalanche-Journal]]'', March 7, 2008|accessdate=March 8, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ssdi.genealogy.rootsweb.com/cgi-bin/ssdi.cgi|title=[[Social Security Death Index]]|publisher=ssdi.genealogy.rootsweb.com|accessdate=March 8, 2008}}</ref>

*'''John Fletcher Brandon, Jr.''' (1921<U+2013>2009), was a farmer, originally from [[Post, Texas|Post]], Texas, who was the [[county judge]] of Lynn County from 1981-2001. He served in the [[United States Army Air Corps]] during [[World War II]]. He was a deacon of the First Baptist Church of Tahoka and was affiliated with Tahoka [[Rotary International]]. He and his wife, the former Mary Caffey, moved to Lubbock in 2005. The couple had two children, Diane and husband Buddy Grammer and Johnny and wife Kathy Brandon, all of Lubbock; four grandchildren, and five great-grandchildren. Brandon is interred at Terrace Cemetery in Post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lubbockonline.com/stories/102109/obi_507122426.shtml|title=Judge J.F. Brandon|publisher=''Lubock Avalanche-Journal]]'', October 20, 2009|accessdate=April 10, 2010}}</ref>

*[[E L Short]] (born 1925) is a farmer, rancher, and businessman in Tahoka who served in both houses of the [[Texas State Legislature]]. He was a member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]] from 1969-1979 and a [[Texas Senate|state senator]] from 1979-1983. He was unseated in the 1982 Democratic primary by [[John T. Montford]], then the [[district attorney]] of [[Lubbock County, Texas|Lubbock County]].

*'''[[Val Joe Walker]]''' (born 1930), a former [[National Football League]] player with the [[Green Bay Packers]] and the [[San Francisco 49ers]].

